column168: Driver was notified via CB that something was leaking from truck.  Immediately pulled over at the next exit (Exit 61) and opened trailer doors.  Product was leaking but could not determine location on trailer.  Notified Pegasus Safety Department who notified authorities.  In the meantime, a sheriff stopped on ramp to questioned driver about stopping on ramp.  Driver explained situation and sheriff notified fire department.  First Response from Nashville handled the clean-up and stabilization of product.  Both sides of interstate were shut down as a precaution.  Wooden pallet was used for bracing in nose and was found broken that caused puncture in lower area of tote.
column169: Will be discussing the circumstances regarding this incident with the shipper, particularly the use of pallets for bracing.  Also, sent fleet message to all our drivers and will also be discussing at our next driver safety meeting on March 13, 2010 regarding cargo securement, hazmat procedures, and general safety items.

column168: While driving west down Manzanares Mesa, outside tire of pup unit got off shoulder of road into soft dirt resulting in overturning of truck and pup.  Western Refining Emergency Response team drilled tank and another Western crude truck off-loaded content of both over-turned units.  Approximately 2-3 bbls leaked from body tank. The spill is isolated to the north side of the roadway. San Juan County Fire Department and the State Police were on the scene providing support to our team. Highway 64 was closed for approximately 4 hours.      The environmental contractor Envirotech preformed remediation at the site.
column169: Instructed driver on managing speed for road conditions.

column169: No additional comments.

column168: A roll-off container containing a hazardous waste was en route to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the container was placed into an approved in-transit storage location pending final delivery.  While the container was being placed into storage, a small amount of material escaped from the rear door of the container at a location where the gasket had not been properly seated.  Facility personnel collected the small amount of material that escaped from the package and placed this, along with all clean-up debris into the container.  In addition, steps were taken to reposition the gasket and reseal the door to preclude a repeat occurrence.  Upon completion of the clean-up activities, the container was reloaded onto a transport vehicle and delivered to the intended receiving facility.
column169: During the clean-up activities, it was discovered that the polyethylene liner placed into the roll-off can impacted the rear door seal preventing it from sealing properly.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver was advised of the suspected cause of the release and was re-instructed on proper steps to take when inspecting and confirming the closure devices used to secure a roll-off container.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading product into customer's tank, product released from the customers tank, as a result of a loose component.  Approximately 25 gallons of free product were released.  Most of the free liquid was contained in the concrete containment pit around the tank, and a small amount impacted some gravel.  King AG personnel performed the cleanup using absorbent material.  King AG will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route to the intended waste management facility when it made a routine stop at an approved in transit storage location pending delivery.  While in storage, a routine inspection identified a small amount of material dripping from the van trailer.  Facility personnel utilizing appropriate personnel protective equipment entered the trailer and identified a 55 gallon non bulk package that had developed a small pinhole leak in the bottom of the container.  It is unclear if the container was punctured by a foreign object or if external corrosion identified on the bottom of the container resulted in the release.  The crew secured the container by placing it into a suitable salvage drum along with all material used to clean-up the area impacted by the release.  This included a small amount of gravel that was impacted by the material as well as absorbents and clean-up debris generated during the response activities.  Once secured, the van was sent to the intended waste management facility where the shipment was received and processed for disposal.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed.  The driver, however, was advised that it is his responsibility to conduct a thorough inspection of each container accepted for transportation and to take appropriate actions in the event a container with suspect structural integrity was indentified.  It was pointed out to the driver and the shipper that excessive corrosion is an indication that a specific container could present a risk during the rigors of transportation.  The driver was further cautioned that a repeat occurrence could result in disciplinary actions.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported UCLX 16024 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with product expulsion from the top of this tank car during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement of UCLX 16024 was stopped. BNSF contract responders inspected UCLX 16024 and reported finding the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured, expelling product onto the tank shell. No ground impact was evident. The responders replaced the frangible disc in kind by 1830 hrs. CST, 3/04/10. UCLX 16024 was then moved to a location in the railyard for these same contract responders to neutralize spillage on the tank shell and water rinse it on 3/05/10.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During routine switching operations an odor was detected from tank car PLMX 137063. The car was isolated onto track 35 at the UPRR Livonia yard without incident or injury. Inspection by UPRR Haz Mat Mgr T. M. Robinson was conducted and Robinson was able, without the assist of a tool, to tighten the valve handle of the vapor valve approximately one quarter turn. The valve plug, which appeared to be tool tight, was removed and re-installed. Robinson inspected all of the other valves and fittings and noted that the odor was no longer present. The car was released onto destination.

All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN response team responded noting shipper's seal intact to the protective housing and manway. Upon inspection by shipper's response team, several manway bolts were found less than tool tight allowing product vapor to be released during movement. Manway gasket repositioned and manway properly secured, car released to destination.

column168: The 5 pm 810 alcohol truck stopped at the main gate to leave. The guard noticed alcohol coming from the drain hose for the dome area. The loader was called to see what the leak was about. Upon inspection, the loader found that the dome lid gasket was pinched. The gasket was reseated and the leak was stopped. One gallon leaked out of the truck. Three pounds spilled on to the concrete and two pounds was in the dome area. The alcohol was cleaned up using absorbant pads and wiped down.

column168: A twenty foot intermodal container GATU 137396 destined for overseas export was reported leaking in the BNSF intermodal parking/staging area. GATU 137396 was carefully moved to the intermodal facility's containment area. A hazardous material/environmental response contractor was called to inspect GATU 137396 and remediate spillage. The responders reported that the doorway inspection of GATU 137396 revealed 55 gallon steel drums loaded in two tiers. One bottom tier drum (UN 1A1/X1.8/300/09/USA/GBC7) at the doorway had leaked from its bottom chime area from abrasion during transit when it came in contact with the raised steel plating at the doorway threshold. This drum was removed from the container and placed into an overpack drum and properly returned to the shipment origin. The remaining lading in GATU 137396 was transloaded into another suitable container properly blocked and braced for furtherance. The now emptied GATU 137396 was cleaned of all spillage.

column168: The USCG was making random inspections when they inspected container HRZU452177-4 and discovered the UN1903 cargo loaded on the rear of the container but no indication of the cargo was listed on the dangerous goods declaration.  The container had other class 8 cargo and was placarded class 8.  A comparison of the original billing with the corrected billing indicated that the shipper incorrectly declared 96 cartons of NA17604 totaling 4483 pounds.  The piece count and weight were correct but the description should have been for UN1903 rather than NA1760.  The shipping paper error was corrected and the shipment released for loading to the ocean vessel pending the USCG release.
column169: The shipper should have been more careful in validating the information loaded into the container against the actual declaration.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: The reference Tank DCIU849061 was reported as leaking about one drop of product every other minute through the side overflow discharge pipe leading from the spill box.  A Dana representative was called to the site and was on site within the hour.  He stated that the leak was due to the expanding product caused by the radiation from the sun.  The leak had stopped.  The evening temperatures probably cooled the tank and reduced the pressure.  The shipment was tendered to the consignee.
column169: Care should be taken in allowing for the outage on tank shipments.  This is expecially important when shipping from a colder climate to a warmer environment.

column168: A vaccuum tanker completed loading at the shipper's location when the overflow vapor recoverey valve splashed out a small amount of material down the side of the trailer into containment.  The driver, who was wearing the proper personal protective equipment, immediately cleaned up the spill with an absorbent material.  The trailer was secured and proceeded on its way to the intended waste management facility where it was off-loaded and cleaned.  The traielr was placed out of service until such time as the vapor recovery valeve could b inspected and repaired if necessary.
column169: The driver had used the trailer the previous day without incident.  The maintenance shop had tested the valve approximately six months previously and it had been working satisfactorily ever since.  In order to prevnt a recurrence, the trailer was placed out of service for the purpose of conducting an inspection of the valve assembly and to make any necessary repairs.

column168: During a routine check, a van trailer loaded with multiple shipments of hazardous material destined for the intended waste disposal facility was found to have a small amount of wetness on the floor.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, a drum was found to be leaking.  It was inverted and a small pinhole leak was found from a corroded portion of the bottom of the drum.  It was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent pads used to cleanup the spilled material.  The loading of the trailer was completed and it proceeded without further incident to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed.  An inspection of the container in question indicated that an area of rust/corrosion on the bottom of the container allowed a small pinhole leak to develop.  The driver was retrained on the inspection process as well as the expected corrective actions that must be taken (e.g. utilize a suitable salvage container) should a container with suspect integrity be identified.  In addition, the shipper was advised of the incident and cautioned to take all necessary steps to insure only sound containers are offered for transportation.

column168: On 03/01/10 at 10:11 hrs., personnel in Russell, KY discovered CSXT 252390, a loaded covered hopper of Ammonium Nitrate, leaking from the bottom of the rail car. The car was isolated away from CSXT personnel. The shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (# 2010-0301-00098). Shipper representative, Virgil Fowler, 706-849-6657, and Greenup County were notified. Quick Response Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. Inspection found the seam where the slope sheet is welded to the hopper chute, had an 18 split in the weld seam. Expanding foam was used to stop the leak and the lading was transferred into CSXT 251267 then forwarded to destination. The spilled product was vacuumed up, placed into drums and returned to the shipper.  This incident did not require a special switch move.

column168: On 03/15/10 at 11:30 hrs., the train crew at the CSX Transportation rail yard in Willard, OH reported GATX 60678, a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid, NOS, "fuming" from the top of the car. The car was moved from W13 to W20 track to isolate it. T. Mannas, CSXT Manager-Hazardous Materials, along with personnel from SWS/Eagle, a CSXT emergency response contractor, inspected the car and noted the following: 1) the vacuum relief device was not in place on the hinged, manway cover but rather lying atop the manway cover, 2) the liquid line valve was fully open and its plug was less than hand tight, 3)  the plug for the air line valve was less than tool tight, 4)  a "donut" style mounting flange was mounted to the top fitting mounting plate. The plug for this "donut" flange was merely set atop its threads. SWS/Eagle personnel secured all fittings in place and the leak stopped.  Note:  This incident did require a special switch move.  Cause Code:  705  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. He has also been instructed that any container that shows evidence of a reduced structural integrity must be either transferred into an appropriate container or placed into a suitable salvage drum for continued transportation.

column168: March 11, 2010: At approximately 10:00AM, CR yard crew BA-3 noted tank car ECUX 461239, load Alcohols, NOS (Isooctyl Alcohol), Combustible Liquid, UN 1987, PG III, leaking from the top of the car in the area of the small protective house (bread box).  Car had not been moved and was noted when crew was moving by it.    Crew notified Yardmaster and Trainmaster notified CR Risk Management.  Risk Management Department notified CR emergency response contractor, REACT, to respond and facilitate the securement of the leak.    Further inspection by REACT noted the leak originating from the 3" liquid line valve operating handle stem packing nut, due to the nut being unsecured.  Further noted during their inspection that the handle had been applied incorrectly (e.g. in order from exterior to the valve, securement nut, valve operating handle, lock washer).  Packing gland nut was tightened, securing the leak; and operating handle assembly reapplied correctly (e.g. in order from exterior to the valve, securement nut, lock washer, operating handle).      No product reported contacting the ground due to slow leak and evaporation.  Car side was wiped down by chemical absorbant pads.  Car secured and okayed for delivery to original consignee, Exxon Mobil, c/o IMTT, Bayonne, NJ (this yard is the interchange yard for delivery to East Jersey Railroad (EJRR) who delivers the cars to the customer.

column168: Trailer IWXP-8192 arrived in UBY at about 1830, there where no signs of a leak or smells of one, at about 1930 we started to break this trailer, about a quarter of the way into the trailer the DSR breaking this noticed some liquid in one of the ribs of the trailer, after looking at the bills of the trailer we decided to move forward and see how much of this was spilled, and to see if we could contain it, At that point we found that all 55 gallons had leaked out of one of the drums, and at that time I had notified Don Andersen at the amount we where dealing with, At this time is when we decide to move it away from the dock and contain it to the trailer, Before we moved it away from the dock I had a opportunity to take pictures and to look at the cause of this, I had found that it had been punctured at the bottom of the drum with about a 4 inch tear in it. column169: To help prevent a recurrence of this happening again, is we need to be totally aware of are surroundings and make Sure we are using the proper handling methods, and if for some reason we do have a incident like this we could have flipped this drum over and put it into a recovery drum and stopped all of the leakage from happening, And far as the receiving service center side we need to make sure we are following all of the company's protocol as well as all of the company's policy. Make Sure you know what you are dealing with before you act, Do Not assume anything

column168: A driver sales rep was unloading trailer 315-4135 out of ULA The trailer consisted of 11 pallets of different heights all floor loaded. When he got to the front of the trailer 5 gallon cans of paint thinner were partially off their pallet with one can completely off the pallet and laying on its side on the floor. The pallets consisted of a single layer of cans of thinner and ctns of paint related products. The said pallet was loosely wrapped with clear wrap and a black top, He picked the can up, noticed that the can was dented but did not see it leaking at that time so he sit it on top on the pallet. The pallet was staged on the dock until it could be loaded. When another driver sales rep went to load the pallet he noticed the wrap on the top of the pallet was wet were the can was sitting. Upon further investigation it was discovered that there was a small pin hole where the dent was and that some of the material was seeping through the hole. Product was not properly wrapped by shipper nor was the shipment secured in the trailer to ensure that product did not slide around. Pallets toward the nose were small pallets so there was space in between the pallets allowing product to shift in transit.
column169: Contact shipper to suggest tighter wrapping of product onto pallet. Discuss with employes importance on securing shipments for transit even if freight looks like it will ride ok.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery at incident location, approximately 15 gallons of free product were released, due to a missing gasket on the external valve.  Approximately 4 gallons released to the asphalt surface, with the remaining 11 gallons being contained into a catch bucket beneath the valve.  The Slay Transportation Co., Inc. driver, along with the customer, Titan Tires, used absorbent material to recover the free product on the asphalt surface, which was containerized into a recovery drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no soils or waters of the state threatened or affected by the release. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a missing gasket, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures, and driver safety, to all personnel.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: On March 7, 2010, at approximately 12:30 p.m. CST,the driver of a tractor-tanker operated by TPG Transport, LLC lost control of the vehicle while leaving the Shannon Hospital Lease 1-3 outside of Iraan, Texas.  As a result, the tractor-tanker rolled over and caught fire while traveling the subject lease road.  The accident caused an breach to the tanker unit in tow.  The subject tanker unit was loaded with 192 barrels of crude oil.  An estimated 5-12 barrels of crude oil were released to the soil surrounding the accident site.  The fire that ensued following the accident consumed the remainder of the cargo load.    At approximately 3:50 p.m. CST, Ms. Celeste Kaban of TPG Transport, LLC, contacted Cura Emergency Services and requested the dispatch of a response crew from Eco-Logical Environmental Services (Eco-Logical), located in Midland, Texas, to assess the site and initiate corrective actions.    The crew from Eco-Logical arrived on site and met with Mr. Ernie Kariainen of TPG Transport, LLC.  On site personnel determined that the release had traveled down the hillside where the accident had occurred, causing the crude oil to pool within a gully.  Personnel from Eco-Logical determined that recovery of the free liquid from the gully was not feasible with the vacuum truck due to the consistency. The crew scheduled additional work for the following day and demobilized from the site.    On March 8, 2010, the crew from Eco-Logical returned to the site and met with Mr. Kariainen.  Crewmembers determined that excavation over the affected roadway (a length of approximately 1/4 mile) was not cost effective.  The lease locations did not want to close the road and an excavation would require the use of a ripper as the road was very hard packed rock.  Mr. Kariainen requested that crewmembers from Eco-Logical pressure wash the affected area on the roadway, down gradient, and recover the rinsate within the gully at the base of the hill.  Crewmembers from Eco-Logical constructed soil dikes along the roadway as containment measures.  The crew began pressure washing the affected areas.    From March 9, 2010 - March 11, 2010, crewmembers from Eco-Logical pressure washed the affected areas on the roadway of the lease site.  The release covered a distance of approxiamtely 1/4 mile, was 6 feet wide at the largest point and, 6 inches deep at the most heavily saturated areas.  The rinsate was recovered with vacuum trucks and sent to Wilson Disposal and Hank's Saltwater for final disposal.  Excavation over the affected area is currently underway.  Personnel from Talon Environmental have been retained to conduct the remainder of excavation/treatment operations for the subject site.

column168: Person authorized sample shipment of a Pesticides, liquid, toxic material, Class 6.1 via Federal Express - Ground. column169: Syngenta Crop Protection will not ship any hazardous material samples from the Stanton, MN facility in the near future. column168: BNSF employees walking by UTLX 202122 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard reported it leaking product from its top fitting area that was running down its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was called and immediately inspected UTLX 202122. The responder reported that the liquid valve was leaking product via its closure plug. Internal pressure within UTLX 202122 was reduced and the responder removed the closure plug for further inspection. The liquid valve was in the closed position, but product appeared to be by-passing this valve's closure or valve seat. Teflon tape was applied to the plug's threads, reinserted and tool tightened. No further product release was evident after the plug was reinstalled. All spillage evaporated. UTLX 202122 was monitored by BNSF responders while awaiting further instructions from the shipper. FRA Movement Approval FRA-10030146 was granted to return UTLX 202122 to its origin for unloading and then forwarding to a qualified repair facility for liquid valve repair or replacement. No further incidents involving UTLX 202122 were reported on the BNSF portion of this return movement.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

ONE APPROXIMATELY 16 OZ, ANOTHER APPROXIMATELY 1 OZ. column168: A BNSF switch crew reported TILX 192597 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the manway closure during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and TILX 192597 awaited inspection from BNSF mechanical personnel, consignee representatives and a shipper response contractor. Consensus opinion was that TILX 192597's manway gasket was not providing a good closure seal, as the manway securement bolts were tight. A new manway gasket was ordered. The replacement gasket was received and then applied by 1000 hrs. PST, 3/04/2010 without further incident. The prior manway gasket broke in two during removal. All spillage evaporated.

column168: While the UTLX 64942 was parked in the KCS Kansas City, MO yard car shop for mechanical equipment repair, a small leak, less than 1 quart, was reported from the bottom outlet flange mount (where bottom outlet flange assembly mounts to bottom of tank car).  KCS mobilized responder service provider (Hazmat Response, Inc. of Olathe, KS www.haz-matresponse.com) who tightened the bottom outlet connection bolts to the tank car shell correcting the release condition.  The bolts were only tightened ~1/8 turn to achieve complete seal and compliant hazmat container. Shipper was notified of incident and advised to have tank car home shopped after unloading to inspect gasket and sealing surfaces as a precaution.     Note to report, item 27, amount in package, was estimated because bulk quantities are provided on shipping paper as "1 Tank Car."  Carrier is not provided specific quantity. This action required by preparer to facilitate data acceptance by DOT IT system edits.    KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 will apply. column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at an in transit storage facility pending final delivery.  While being checked in, an inspection identified a small amount of material had escaped from a non bulk package onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  It was discovered that a small leak developed on the bottom of one of the non bulk packages.  The response crew placed the damaged container into a suitable salvage container and proceeded to clean and decontaminate the trailer floor that was impacted by the release.  All material used was collected and placed into the salvage drum along with the leaking container.  Once secured, the trailer was placed into storage pending delivery and receipt at the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was initially accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver as well as the shipper have been advised of the incident and have been cautioned to insure that all containers are thoroughly inspected to insure that any container showing evidence of a reduction in structural integrity be addressed before accepting for transportation.  The driver was re-instructed on his responsibility to take appropriate actions should a suspect container be found during a pre transportation inspection.

column168: Drivers were dispatched to a customer location in order to pick-up and transport an intermediate bulk package containing a hazardous waste destined for disposal.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at an in transit storage location for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload quantities for continued transportation.  Upon arrival at the in transit storage area, facility personnel initiate the process of transferring the container to an alternative van trailer.  It was at this point that the individual moving the container identified a small amount of material leaking from a seam on the container.  Facility personnel secured the vehicle and initiated the transfer of the material from the initial container into an alternative container.  This operation was completed without incident.  In addition, the minimal amount of material that was released was clean-ed up and all debris was placed into the container that was found to be leaking.  This container, along with the replacement container was placed onto the containing transporter’s van trailer and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the driver arrived at the shipper's location, the container was inspected and no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver will continue to inspect each container before loading and will take all steps necessary if a damaged or suspect container is identified.

column162: MANAGER ENV PROG AND DANGEROUS GOODS
column168: Package containing Anti-Cribbing compound was prepared by Woodstar Products, Inc. for shipment via United States Postal Service (USPS) from Wisconsin address to address in the Netherlands.  Package made first flight from ORD to PHL on 03/17/2010 and departed for AMS on 03/18/2010.  Upon arrival in AMS it was discovered that the 1-gallon can of brown anti-cribbing had leaked.  Product may be classified as a Class II Combustible Liquid, which is not acceptable for USPS international mailing.  Leak was cleaned in AMS prior to departure to PHL, where subsequent cleaning was done.  Package had no labels or markings.
column169: Woodstar Products should have designated and trained shipping personnel familiar with US Postal Service rules.  A trained employee would know that this product was not suitable for sending via the US Postal Service for international destination.  Other, more suitable shipping methods are available for this product.

column168: AFTER UNLOADING AT CAPE GIRARDEAU, MO ALL VALVES, CUPS, AND LIDS WERE SECURE.  NO LEAKS PRESENT.  AFTER LEAVIMG THE FACILITY IN ROUTE FOR RINECO, (BENTON) I MADE A STOP AT LONEOAK, AR TO TAKE MY BREAK.  I DID A WALK AROUND AND SAW NO LEAKS ON GROUND.  I WAS AWAKEN BY LONEOAK SHERRIFF'S DEPT. STATING I HAD A LEAK & WAS ON THE GROUND.  IT APPEARED AS THOUGH SEAL WAS LEAKING ON THE LARGE FITTING ATTACHED TO THE CENTER DISCHARGE VALVE, (BOTTOM).  THE AREA AFFECTED ON GROUND WAS APPROXIMATELY 3 1/2 FT X 2 FT.  IT WAS ON HARD SURFACE ON PACKED SBZ GRAVEL MIX.  RINECO WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS CURRENT SUPERVISION.  PERSONNEL WAS DISPATCHED AND CLEANUP WAS MADE.
column169: OUR UNLOADING PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN RE-ADDRESSED WITH OUR DRIVERS TO ENSURE THEY DOUBLE-CHECK THE DISCHARGE VALVE AND CONFIRM THAT THE GASKET IS IN PLACE BEFORE LEAVING UNLOADING FACILITY.  THIS IS A DRIVER'S OVERSIGHT WHICH IS PUNISHABLE BY A WRITTEN WARNING.

column168: VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING TO FAST FOR A 50 MPH CORNER IN THE HIGHWAY.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO HEED A WARNING SIGN AND ENTERED THE CORNER TO FAST TO SAFELY NEGOTIATE IT.  HE DRIFTED INTO THE ONCOMING TRAFFIC LANE.  SAW A VEHICLE COMING AT HIM AND JERKED THE WHEEL BACK TO THE RIGHT.  THE TRUCK OVERTURNED.  THE TRAILER FRONT LEFT CORNER HIT FIRST.  THE SHOCK TO THE TRAILER CAUSED THE WELD SEAM TO FAIL. THE PRODUCT IGNITED.
column169: ROADWAY SIGNAGE COULD BE BETTER.  A BLINKING YELLOW LIGHT ON THE 50 MPH CURVE WARNING SIGN MAY HAVE GOTTEN THE ATTENTION OF THE DRIVER.  DRIVER ATTENTION NEEDS TO IMPROVE.

column168: On March 11, 2010 at approximately 5:30 am, CDT, the driver of a tractor-trailer operated by Land Express- a division of Evans Deliver Company lost control of the vehicle while traveling westbound on I-26, near exit 199. Subsequently, the tractor overturned damaging both the tractor and trailer. As a result, the tractor released approximately 100 gallons of diesel fuel onto the asphalt shoulder. The fuel traveled down gradient and into a storm drain and nearby outfall with standing storm water. The impact also damaged an undetermined amount of containers, resulting in the release of approximately 2,240 gallons of a liquid organophosphorus compound (Class 6.1, UN2810).
column169: The crew from Moran arrived on site and met with representatives from the PRFD and SC DHEC to discuss the cleanup operations. The tractor-trailer was uprighted and Moran personnel donned level B PPE and entered the trailer. The product was pumped from the damaged containers. The damaged containers were then removed from the trailer and staged for disposal The remaining product was then transferred from the damaged trailer and shipped to its original destination. Moran personnel applied granular absorbents to the freestanding product. The absorbents were worked in with hand tools and collected for disposal. Moran personnel then utilized a vacuum truck to collect the free product from the catch basn and outfall area. Cleanup operations continued until no visual or olfactory indicators of product could be obsevred. The area was secured and the crew de-moblized. Moran personnel re-mobilized to the site at a later date to excavate the affected areas of soil.

column168: GATX 57621 was involved in an overspeed coupling due to contamination on the surface of retarder brakes during hump yard switching operations.  The car exitted the retarders at approximately 16 MPH and coupled to a standing cut of cars.    The overspeed coupling and product surge resulted in the safety vent assembly baffle, rupture disc and inspection port being damaged and allowing liquid product and vapor to be released.  In addition, the locking bar on the fill hole was broken.    Emergency response contractor, Hepaco, Inc., responded and secured the car to stop the vapor release and made temporary repairs to the fill hole and safety vent.  Rescar responded and replaced the entire safety vent assembly and repaired the locking bar mechanism to stop all liquid and vapor release.  FRA mechanical and hazmat inspectors examined and approved the car prior to movement.      The car was returned loaded to orgin for off-loading and then empty to a certified tank car shop for a complete inspection and final repairs, testing and requalification.  All movements after the initial field repairs were made under FRA Movement Approval FRA-10030178.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A 55 GALLON DRUM OF LIQUID WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE SEAL AND SEAM, LOCATED AROUND THE LID OF THE DRUM DUE FROM LID NOT TIGHTENED. column169: BETTER SECUREMENT OF CAP, BUNGS OR LIDS ON DRUMS. DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF PAILS, DRUMS, TOTES OR MISCELLANEOUS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column162: SR MGR INDUSTRIAL SAFETY AND ENV
column168: WHILE ENROUTE TO CUSTOMER, FOUND IN THE TRAILER WAS ONE GALLON PAIL.  FOUND INSIDE OF A BOX, WITH A PIN-SIZED HOLE ON THE SIDE OF ONE OF THE PAIL WHERE PRODUCT FOUND LEAKING OUT. THE HAZ MAT WAAS BLOCKED IN BY AN EMPTY SKID AND A NAIL VERATED INTO THE SIDE OF THE CARTON WHILE IN TRANSIT.  FURTHER INSPECTED THE OUTSIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND NOTICED A HOLE IN THE EXTERIOR ON ONE SIDE, NEAR BOTTOM.  THIS AREA MATCHED WHERE THE ONE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS LOCATED AND CORRESPONDED TO THE PIN SIZED HOLE IN IT.
column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: TRAILER ARRIVED 431 FROM 621, DISCOVERED WHEN TRAILER WAS OPENED, LIQUID WAS FOUND ON THE FLOOR, UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, TWO PCS OF STEEL AT 1000LBS, PRO NUMBER 313-898691 HAD FALLEN ON TOP OF THE TOTE AND CRUSHED THE TOP CORNER AND BUSTED IT, LEAKED APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO FLOOR OF TRAILER.  AN LICENSED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, ALONG WITH FACILITY PERSONNEL, CLEANED UP AND CONTAINED THE LIQUID.  THE ER TEAM TRANSFERRED PRODUCT OUT OF THE DAMAGED TOTE INTO A NEW TOTE PER SHIPPER'S AUTHORIZATION.  THE AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED SALVAGE DRUMS AND ARE BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION.
column169: TOTES, DRUMS, CYLINDERS, AND PAILS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACING USING MTY PALLETS, AIR BAGS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. TEMPORARY STORAGE AREAS FOR PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE KEPT IN A SAFE ENVIRONMENT TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.

column168: UCLX 16236 was noted by carrier personnel with product dripping from the bottom of the tank shell above the wheels of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and contained the drip and made an initial inspection of the leak source.  This is a jacketed tank car and access to the tank shell in order to fully assess the source of the release was not possible.  The car was noted dripping on the Weyerhaeuser Lead track while being switched into the destination plant facility.  The decision was made with concurrence of local emergency responders to contain the drip and move the car the short distance into the plant where the car was destined for immediate unloading.  The cause is suspected to be a tank shell failure due to corrosion but a definite cause for this release is pending further investigation.    After unloading the car will be cleaned and purged of product and sent to a tank car shop for further inspection and repairs.

column168: TILX 199192 was reported to be releasing ethanol on the mainline in Boone, IA.  Inspection of the car found the bottom outlet valve unpinned and open and the bottom outlet valve cap hanging on the safety chain.  The valve was closed by Transportation personnel and the cap was reapplied by Mechanical department personnel.      Inspection inside the car found approximately twelve to eighteen inches of product remaining in the car, equating to approximately 27000 gallons of product released over an unknown distance leading in to Boone.      Inspection of the valve handle securement pin (breaking pin) revealed the seal end of the pin was broken off, allowing the pin to come out of the handle securement bracket and for the valve handle to fall to an open position.
column169: UP is investigating this incident to determine how and why the pin broke, the valve came open, and the safety cap became unscrewed. These components were not originally secured by UP, and were not handled in transit by UP.

column168: All,     I just wanted to provide you all with a brief recap of the hose failure this morning. Bob truck AH1130 was on our yard after returning from a delivery at 11:30am. At 11:55am I was loading an aqua tanker when I heard a loud “pop” and hissing, I looked up and immediately saw an ammonia vapor cloud approximately 15 feet high. I ran around to the water cannon turned it on the leak and began knocking down the remaining visible vapor, within 30-45 seconds of the hose failure the visible vapor had subsided and only residual vapor pressure was being emitted. I kept the water cannon on the hose and called Butch Johnson at 11:58am, followed by the Fire Department at 12:00pm and NRC at 12:05pm. The Columbus fire Department arrived at 12:07pm surveyed the situation and left at approximately 12;30pm.  The hose was protected by a hydrostat which did not release  I am shipping the hose and the hydro to Concord to try and determine if the hose or the hydro is at fault for the failure. I have replaced the hose and the hydrostatic relief and checked for leaks, everything looks good to go. (pictures can be opened with windows picture and fax viewer)              Anthony L. Reynolds    Facility Manager    Airgas Specialty Products     310 Brennan Road    Columbus Ga, 31903    Office 706-689-9783    Fax 678-530-1131    Cell 706-992-8191    anthony.reynolds@airgas.com

column168: Vertex Chemical Corporation’s contract carrier driver delivered a load of Sodium Hypochlorite to its consignee, Tyson Foods in Dexter, MO.  The driver arrived at the consignee site and unloaded the product into a tank at the consignee site.  There was not sufficient room in the tank to hold the entire load and the tank overflowed approximately 250 gallons at the end of the transfer.    Vertex was notified of the situation and is reporting the incident.  The spilled product was diluted with water and directed by hose into the drain that feeds into the wastewater treatment system for the plant.
column169: This incident will be reviewed with all Vertex Memphis carrier drivers and proper unloading procedures and reporting procedures reviewed.  The driver was disciplined.  Product clean up was conducted by the consignee.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines Inc. Driver was unloading unleaded gasoline at a customer location when he noticed fuel leaking from the vapor recovery. The driver immediately stopped the flow of product but approximately 5-10 gallons spilled on the concrete containment area. The driver was able to clean up with spill with spill pads. The driver had taken stick readings on the tank prior to delivery and received a measurement of 9.5 inches. The driver was to deliver 7000 gallons on gas. Upon investigation of the tank it was determined that the tank did not have overfill protection and the driver exceeded the 90% fill rule by 100 gallons.
column169: The customer's tank will have the overfill protection added prior to more deliveries. Driver will be retrained on company unloading procedures. The driver will also have an incident prevention observation conducted on him.

column168: Shipper had left the air valve open and had failed to insert the air valve plug and seal.  When the tanker car was coupled to another car for spotting, a small amount of acid was released from the open air valve.  The released acid contacted a railroad employee but no injury occurred.
column169: We contacted the supplier of this product and requested that they re-train their employees on the required loading procedures (i.e. closing the air valve, inserting the air valve plug and applying the seal.)  The supplier agreed and are planning to reinforce with all loading personnel the importance of final securement, and will determine if any further action is required.

column168: A roll-off trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip a New York Conservation Officer following the Clean Harbors vehicle noticed a small amount of liquid leaking from the roll-off container and pulled the vehicle over. The vehicle was escorted by the officer to Exit 49 Tandem Terminal on the NY state thruway in order to indeitfy, container and remediate the situation.  A company representative met the driver and inspected the cargo.  The load appeared to be dry and it was Clean Harbor's position that the leaking material was residual rain water that had collected in the rail of the roll-off frame. The condition of the roll-off can did indicate some minor defects and visually, it did appear that the liquid was leaking from the cargo compartment even though no visible liquid was observed in the roll-off. The driver inspected the closure device and re-secured the load to the satisfaction of the COnservation Officer.  The driver was released and proceeded to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Upon inspection at the Tandem Terminal it was determined the can was leaking from the frame; no water was present in the roll-off which was lined properly. Rain water in the frame was suspected as being the substance leaking.  The driver has been re instructed to insure that during rain events that the vehicle is adequaltely tarped and any residual precipitation is removed to insure that rain water does not eneter the cargo compartment resulting in a release or threat of release.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route to an in-transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck-load quantities for continued transportation to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver conducted a routine load inspection and discovered a small amount of material had escaped from on of the intermediate bulk packages being transported.  It appeared that the weight of a container loaded on top of damaged container caused the package to split open allowing a small amount of material to escape onto the trailer floor.  The driver immediately contacted his hoe dispatcher and a response crew was dispatched to the scene.  Upon arrival, the response crew stabilized the damaged container and placed in an alternative vehicle for transport to a safe location where the container could be repackaged for continued transportation.  This activity was completed without further incident.  In addition, the released material was re containerized and all debris generated from the response activities was collected and placed into the original container for disposal.  Once repacked, the shipment, along with all clean-up debris was sent for disposal at the intended facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, loading personnel and the driver were advised of the suspected cause of the release.  The individuals involved will be re-trained on the loading requirements as it relates to safe loading practices where containers will be stacked upon each other.  Special care must be taken to insure that the container on the bottom level can withstand the superimposed weight placed upon it.

column168: Railcar GATX-20738 was switched into Syngenta’s Omaha, NE plant at approximately 10:30 AM on Thursday morning March 18, 2010.  Plant operations personnel noticed approximately 5 gallons of product sprayed & splattered on top / sides of the railcar.  Material appeared to have been released through the pressure relief valve on the top of the railcar.  All manway and dip-tube dome seals were in place and unbroken.  Car was moved to a contained unloading area where material was removed from outside of railcar with soap, water, mops & rags.  Loss of product appeared minimal.  Material on the railcar was both dried & wet, indicating the possibility of multiple releases of the product from the relief valve during transit.  Incident appears to be the result of a failed pressure relief valve or a relief valve that did not reseat.
column169: Railcar was sent to the local rail repair shop in Omaha, NE when product was unloaded.  All spilled product has been cleaned & disposed of properly.  Faulty relief valve will be replaced / repaired as necessary.

column168: ON MARCH 1, 2010 HENIFF DRIVER WENT TO THE CITGO REFINERY TO PICK UP A BULK LOAD OF XYLENE.  THE TRAILER WAS LOADED BY THE PLANT PERSONNEL AND THE DRIVER WAS PROVIDED PLACARDS AND SHIPPING PAPERS REQUIRED FOR TRANSPORT.  THE DRIVER CHECKED THAT ALL OPENINGS WERE SECURE BEFORE DRIVING ON THE PUBLIC ROADWAY.  SHORTLY AFTER LEAVING THE PLANT THE DRIVER OBSERVED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TANK.  THE DRIVER WAS IN 800 BLOCK OF STATE STREET IN LOCKPORT, IL.  THE DRIVER STOPPED THE TRUCK TO CHECK FOR THE PROBLEM.  AT THAT POINT THE TRUCK DID NOT MOVE AGAIN UNTIL THE PROBLEM WAS SOLVED.  THE FAILURE WAS LISTED AS A GASKET WHICH IS PARTIALLY CORRECT.  THE PROBLEM WAS NOT THAT THE DOME GASKET FAILED WHICH IT DIDN'T BUT RATHER THE DOME GASKET WAS NOT IN PLACE.  THE DOME WAS SECURED BUT THE SEAL WAS NOT MADE.  THE LOADER AT THE SHIPPING FACILITY SECURED THE DOME AND SEALED THE DOME LID AFTER LOADING.  THE DRIVER CHECKED AND IT APPEARED THAT THE DOME WAS TIGHT AND EVERYTHING WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  THE FACT IS AT SOME POINT THE DOME GASKET WAS REMOVED FROM THE DOME COLLAR AND PLACE OFF TO THE SIDE ON THE TOP OF THE TANK.  HOW THIS HAPPENDED CAN ONLY BE EXPLAINED AS HUMAN ERROR.  BUT BECAUSE OF THIS THE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK. AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AND HENIFF MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON THE SCENE THEY IMMEDIATELY DISCOVERED WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS.  THEY PUT THE DOME GASKET BACK IN PLACE AND THEN TIGHTEN THE DOME LID SECUREDLY.  THIS WAS ALL THAT WAS NEEDED TO FIX THE PROBLEM.  THE XYLENE THAT HAD LEAKED WAS ON THE ASPHALT ROADWAY.  THE LOCKPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT PUT DOWN 6 BAGS OF OIL DRY TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL FROM THE ASPHALT.  HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORP DISPATCHED TWO PERSONS TO THE SCENE AT THE REQUEST OF HENIFF TRANSPORTATION SYSTEMS TO PICK UP THE CONTAMINATED OIL DRY.  THE CONTAMINATED OIL DRY WAS SWEPT UP AND REMOVED FROM THE ROADWAY AND PLACED INTO TWO 55 DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WERE TAKEN BACK TO THEIR FACILITY AND WERE MANIFESTED TO BE DISPOSED OF AT POLLUTION CONTROL INDUSTRIES IN EAST CHICAGO, IN.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: 03/31/2010: At approximately 12:43am, CR North Yard crew FD46 was switching rail cars in yard to make up local delivery train, via remote control operations, utilizing NS locomotive 5242.  After making coupling to 29 cars on track 3 Class, crewmember noted a puff of smoke originating from the top of tank car GATX 60775, load Hydrochloric Acid (class 8, UN 1789, PGII, RQ).      Further investigation by Conrail supervision noted no liquid reside on top or sides of car, but ocassional puffing of vapor originated from the non-reclosing pressure relief device (safety vent/frangible disc) when car was moved.  Car isolated on north side of yard office building and just south of Mt. Elliott overpass.  Conrail emergency response contractor Eagle SWS, Findlay, OH, was requested to respond.  Further inspection found the safety vent's 165 pound-rated frangible disc (Oseco design) had ruptured as designed due to internal pressure surge.  Ruptured disc removed and replaced in kind with new disc, safety vent closures made secure.  No clean up/decontamination was required due no loss of liquid product.      FD46 crew members P. Morales and S. Sparre requested being taken to a clinic to be checked out.  Trainmaster T. Goad escorted both to clinic, and both were found fit for duty and returned back to the yard.
column169: No additional comments.

FOLLOWED DECISION TREE TO UNKNOWN RESPONSE SHEET.  PH NEUTRAL; TREATED AS FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  ABSORBED SPILLED LIQUIDS.  PKG BROUGHT TO DMP AREA FOR PROCESSING.

column168: 1 PALLET OF 4 TOTAL IN SHIPMENT WAS STACKED ON TOP OF ANOTHER.  PALLET SHIFTED IN TRANSIT FALLING AGAINST A LOAD-BAR THAT WAS PLACED BEHIND THE PALLET TO SECURE.  1 BOX (CONTAINING TWO 12.5L CANS) ON SAID PALLET CAME INTO CONTACT WITH SAID LOAD BAR DENTING ONE OF THE CANS CAUSING SMALL CRACKS IN THE CAN ON EITHER SIDE OF THE DENT APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES FROM THE TOP OF THE CAN.  AS THE PALLET WAS SITTING AT A 15 DEGREE ANGLE, A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LEAKED AT OF THE CRACKS.  SPILLAGE HAD DRIED BY THE TIME DAMAGE WAS DISCOVERED AND SHIPMENT WAS NO LONGER LEAKING -- NO CLEANUP REQUIRED.
column169: A LOAD STRAP SHOULD BE USED INSTEAD OF A BAR TO ELIMINATE THE POTENTIAL FOR THE SHIPMENT TO SHIFT IN TRANSIT.

column169: WE WILL PRACTICE ONLY GOING INTO SKID 3/4 OF THEORY TO PREVENT GOING INTO THE SKID IN FRONT.

column168: DURING TAXI TO CARGO FACILITY, BLDG 23, COCKPIT CREW SMELLED ODOR COMING FROM LOAD POSITION AL IN MDII FREIGHTER.  JRK TOWER ADVISED WHO RESPONDED/DISPATCHED HAZMAT TEAM TO A/C.  AFTER INSPECTION OF A/C NO LEAKAGE WAS FOUND.  A/C RELEASED.  AFTER OFFLOAD OF A/C, PALLET POSITION WHICH CONTAINED HAZMAT MENTIONED WAS CHECKED.  FOUND PINHOLE IN ONE STEEL DRUM.  AMOUNT LEAKED APPROX. .1LTR.  CLEANED UP AND DRUM WAS ISOLATED FOR PICKUP.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: DRUM WAS ON SKID WITH 4 TOTAL PCS.  SECOND SKID CONTAINING 2 DRUMS WAS BEING MOVED.  WHEN EMPLOYEE WAS MOVING SKID WITH 2 DRUMS THE BLADES OF A FORKLIFT WERE PROTRUDING THROUGH SKID AND WHEN MOVED INTO TRAILER EMPLOYEE PUSHED FORK BLADE INTO DRUM DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF MOVING LOAD.
column169: EMPLOYEE INVOLVED WITH THIS INCIDENT WILL BE REQUIRED TO COMPLETE RETRAINING COMPLETELY ON PROPER HANDLING OF DRUMS.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DRIVER FUELING AND WHEN DOING INSPECTION, NOTICED PINK PAINT-LIKE SUBSTANCE LEAKING FROM THE FLOOR OF TRIALER RIGHT OVER TANDEMS ON DRVR SIDE. SLOW LEAK.  CALLED ENVIROMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC FOR CLEAN-UP ASSISTANCE AND THEY SENT RESPONSE TEAM TO SITE.  HAD TO UNLOAD 1/2 REAR OF TRAILER.  FOUND ONE LEAKING 55 GALLON DRUM.  DRUM WAS ALLEGEDLY SUBJECT TO CORROSION/RUST ON THE BOTTOM PER ON SITE CLEAN UP CORDINATOR.  APPEARS THAT DRUM FAILED DUE TO CRACK IN BOTTOM.  RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS.  ABOUT 30 GALLONS STILL IN THERE.  MOVED DAMAGED CONTAINER WITH REMAINING 30 GALLONS INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SENT IT ON TO CUSTOMER.  GENERATED ONE DRUM OF WASTE, INSTRUCTED EMI TO PROPERLY DISPOSE.
column169: RECOMMEND THAT SHIPPERS USE MORE STRUCTURALLY SOUND CONTAINERS FOR PACKAGING AND USE BETTER SECUREMENT METHODS TO PREVENT CONTACT DURING TRANSIT THAT MY COMPROMISE INTEGRITY OF PACKAGING.

column14: Columbia Blvd Ramp to I5 South
column168: 1100 - Driver entered a sharp curve going too fast; he hit the breaks and the tractor/ trailer rolled onto its side.  1105 - 911 was called/ Fire Dept and Police arrived on the scene at 1115.  1120 - I called Gerlock Towing and PSC Environmental.  1130 - I, Paul Marlett, arrived at the scene.  1135 - Ramon Ortiz was taken by ambulance to Emanuel Hospital for check up.  1140 - NRC Environmental arrived on scene. (PSC Dispatched them)  Brain McNamara (ODOT) arrived at scene.  1300 - Another Chemical Transfer tractor/ trailer arrived at scene to transfer product.  1350 - Mechanic arrived at scene to take off internal/ external valves in order to transfer product; only way we could get product out.  1500 - NRC Environmental vacuum truck arrived at scene and pumped out the product.  1700 - Pump out completed.  1710 - Gerlock Towing uprighted the tractor/ trailer.  1750- NRC Envrionmental finished cleaning up the scene until around 1815.

column168: A BNSF yard crew member reported PVCX 13453 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) in the railyard with fresh product on its side shell. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected PVCX 13453. Inspection revealed the leak source at the liquid eduction line's closure cap. This closure cap was tight, but was not sealing. Internal pressure within PVCX 13453 was reduced and the closure cap was removed for a detailed inspection. The cap was not cross-threaded. Responders wiped the threaded connection and applied Teflon tape to the cap's threads. The closure cap was then reapplied and tool tightened. Product spillage was neutralized with baking soda and then washed away. Response was concluded by 1200 hrs. MST, 3/03/2010. No further product release was evident in subsequent rail movements of PVCX 13453 in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Pacific West personnel discovered product dripping due to a loose bottom outlet cap.  The cap was tightened stopping the release.   The tank car was re-inspected with no other exceptions found. Shipper was notified via Chemtrec. (B)UPRR yard personnel reported tank car GATX 80556 released an unknown amount of product from the top of tank car in the Milford Utah.  Leon Hendrickson, UPRR Hazardous Materials Manager was notified. Mr. Hendrickson notified UPRR emergency response contractor to respond. Inspection revealed the tank car had released approximately 10 gallons of product from the pressure relief device.  Upon inspection it was determined that the release was a result of deteriorated and aged o rings.  The o-rings were replaced.  The tank car was closed, secured re-inspected and released to destination.  Shipper was notified by Chemtrec.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was at a customer location (retail gas station) doing a pump over. The station was closed as they were upgrading their tanks. Driver had an empty tanker at the time of incident. Driver was in the process of moving mid grade unleaded gasoline over to the empty unleaded cargo tank when the hose he was using ruptured, spilling between 10 and 50 gallons of gas. The driver immediately stopped the flow of product but upon doing so the gas was ignited, this eventually caught the driver, tractor, empty trailer, and another vehicle that was parked on site on fire. The fire was contained by the fire department. The driver was transported to the hospital where he later passed away due to the injuries.
column169: This incident is currently under investigation. All hosed and equipment were recovered and are being inspected.

column168: A BNSF train operating on Kansas City Terminal Railway Co. (KCT) trackage was stopped and train crew reported that entrained GFSX 101238 (AAR C113, three compartment covered hopper, built 06/1974) was leaking product from the B-end bottom hopper outlet chute. BNSF mechanical and contract responders were dispatched to investigate and remediate spillage. Mechanical responders reported that the B-end bottom outlet's slope sheet had a weld crack at an exterior vertical joint. This crack was sealed with expanding foam material. The contract responders located spillage along the right-of-way and shoveled this ground spillage into containers. After GFSX 101238's arrival in the railyard, it was reinspected by BNSF mechanical personnel and the temporary repairs were found to be secure with no further evidence of product leaks. GFSX 101238 was setout of the train and then carefully moved to a staging location in the railyard for product transfer to another suitable covered hopper. Product transfer was completed by 2000 hrs. CDT, 3/25/2010 without further incident. Recovered spillage was sifted and cleaned of all ground contaminates; the pure product was returned to the lading during the product transfer process.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the mechanical fitness and package integrity of railcars in the pre-loading queue.

column168: A BNSF mechanical inspection in the railyard of GATX 72219 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) revealed that it had leaked product from the manway closure during rail movement. The nearby loader of GATX 72219 sent a responder to secure the manway closure. The responder reported that the manway securement bolts were tight; but the manway gasket was damaged and it was replaced. After gasket installation, the manway cover was secured and the responder wiped spillage from the tank shell. Response was completed by 0945 hrs. CDT, 3/23/2010.

column168: Driver was heading south when he went off the right side of the road and overcorrected. The gas truck overturned on the road before continuing off the left side of the road.  There was a minor release of propane and motor fuel.  The small propane release was coming from the hose damaged in the accident.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed. A pull-away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICAL MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED, RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: BAXTER'S GTS WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL DISCOVERED DAMAGE TO THE OUTER PACKAGING OF THE BOXES CONTAINING BATTERIES WHILE THE PALLETTED BOXES WERE BEING UNLOADED FROMA DHL GLOBAL TRUCK AT THE BAXTER RECEIVING DOCK.  BAXTER ACCEPTED SHIPMENT OF THE GOODS BECAUSE COMPANY PERSONNEL WERE CONCERNED THAT SENDING THE SHIPMENT BACK VIA DHL TRUCK WOULD EXACERBATE THE DAMGED CONDITIONS OBSERVED.  BAXTER NOTIFIED DHL GLOBAL OF THIS INCIDENT ON THE SAME DATE.  HISTORICAL DETAILS THE SHIPMENT ORIGINATED FROM SINGAPORE IN JANUARY 2010 AND WAS DESTINED FOR BUFFALO GROVE, IL.  THE SHIPMENT HAD SEVERAL GROUND TRANSFER LEGS AND WAS STORED IN THE DHL GLOBAL WAREHOUSE IN FRANKLIN PARK, IL.  WE WERE UNABLE TO DETERMINE HOW AND WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURRED BUT ALL OBSERVATIONS SUGGEST THAT THE DAMAGE LIKELY RESULTED BECAUSE OF HANDLING IN TRANSIT.  THE DAMAGE TO THE SHIPMENT HAPPENDED PRIOR TO ARRIVING AT THE BAXTER FACILITY IN BUFFALO GROVE, IL.  BEFORE OFF-LOADING THE PALLETS FROM THE DHL GLOBAL TRUCK, THE ATTACHED PROTOS WERE TAKEN TO DOCUMENT THE DAMGED BATTERIES.  OF THE 10 PALLETS IN THE SHIPMENT, 2 PALLETS HAD DAMAGED OUTER PACKAGING.  ON THESE 2 PALLETS, 9 BOXES WERE TORN, CRUSHED OR DENTED.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS/ACTIONS TAKEN  1. BAXTER NOTIFIED DHL OF THE EVENT AND IS AWAITING DHL'S FULL INVESTIGATION.  2. DHL'S INITIAL INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT DAMAGE TO CARTONS WAS OBSERVED BY ONE OF THE AIR CARRIERS INVOLVED.  3. BAXTER COMMUNICATED WITH THE SINGAPORE ORIGIN/SHIPPER SITE TO CONFIRM THAT APPROPRIATE PACKAGING AND SHIPPING PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED.  4. THE SINGAPORE SITE THAT OFFERED THE BATTERIES FOR SHIPMENT INDICATED THAT SINGAPORE AIRLINES, WHICH ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT FOR THE FIRST LEG OF TRAVEL FOUND THE SHIPMENT ACCEPTABLE FOR TRANSPORT.  5. BAXTER RECOMMENDS THAT DHL NOTIFIES ALL OF THE CARRIERS INVOLVED OF THE INCIDENT.  6. BAXTER WILL BE REQUESTING THAT DHL GLOBAL IMPROVE THEIR HANDLING AND INSPECTIONS OF THE PACKAGES WHILE IN TRANSIT SINCE ALL INSPECTIONS AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION INDICATED NO PROBLEMS OR DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGES.

column168: On March 11th, 2010, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. column168: PRIOR TO LOADING THE TRAILER OUR DRIVER INSPECTED IT TO VERIFY THAT IT WAS CLEAN, DRY AND ODOR FREE.  AS PART OF THE INSPECTION PROCESS THE DRIVER REMOVED THE EXTERNAL VALVE ON THE TRAILER.  HE INSPECTED EVERYTHING AND PUT THE EXTERNAL VALVE BACK IN PLACE.  WHEN HE PUT THE VALVE BACK IN PLACE HE FAILED TO MAKE SURE THAT IT WAS SITTING FLUSH WHICH MADE IT SLIGHTLY OUT OF POSITION.    WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT ASHLAND CHEMICAL TO OFF LOAD THE TRAILER HE OPENED UP THE INTERNAL VALVE WHILE THE EXTERNAL VALVE REMAINED CLOSED.  PRESSURE BUILT UP AGAINST THE CLOSED EXTERNAL VALVE AND PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE VALVE STEM.  THIS OCCURRED BECAUSE IT WAS NOT INSTALLED PROPERLY.  THE CUSTOMER HOOKED UP A HOSE TO THE DISCHARGE VALVE, OPENED THE EXTERNAL VALVE, AND OFFLOADED THE TRAILER.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  THIS PRODUCT WAS COLLECTED IN A CONTAINMENT AREA AND EVENTUALLY PLACED INTO A DRUM AND DISPOSED OF.  THE EVENT OCCURRED DUE TO DRIVER ERROR.
column169: IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE DELIVERY THE DRIVER WAS BOUGHT INTO THE OFFICE AND WE DISCUSSED WHAT OUR INVESTIGATION REVEALED.  THE CUSTOMER PROVIDED US WITH PICTURES OF THE VALVE AND WE SHOWED THE DRIVER EXACTLY WHAT WENT WRONG.  HE WAS RE-TRAINED ON THE PROPER INSTALLATION OF AN EXTERNAL VALVE AND ITS COUNTER PARTS.  THIS WILL BE DOCUMENTED IN THE DRIVER'S FILE.  WE WILL ALSO DISCUSS THIS EVENT AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS.

column168: Employee was fueling at a tank and pulled away before disconnecting the hose from the tank.   There was a release of approximately 50 gallons.  Police and Fire departments responded. column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed. A pull-away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

On 3/28/10 at approximately 0420 hours, a Dist Tech tanker carrying xylene was involved in a single vehicle accident.  This caused the release of approximately 25 gallons of xylene (UN1307, pg III, class 3).  The release impacted the soil ditch line.  The local fire dept., OH EPA, and environmental contractor (Evergreen) arrived on site to contain the release.  The cargo was transferred into a new tanker.  The impacted soil was excavated, containerized, and disposed of properly by the contractor.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was loading gasoline at the loading facility to be delivered at a customer location. While loading the driver grabbed the riser to compartment 5 and set the load to 2500 gallons for the 2500 gallon compartment. The driver should have used a different riser as he already had 827 gallons loaded in compartment 5. The driver noticed fuel leaking from the compartment. The driver hit the emergency shut off switch but approximately 320 gallons spilled into the containment area. No fuel reached soil or drains. The BP environmental representative was on site and approved the clean up.
column169: It was determined that the probe in compartment 5 was not working properly and will repaired prior to future use. It was also determined that the driver was distracted and therefore loaded the wrong compartement. The driver will be re-trained on loading procedures and will have incident prevention observations conducted on him by safety supervisors.

column168: An inbound train inspection on the main track in the railyard by a BNSF mechanical car inspector revealed entrained SHPX 207627 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) was leaking product from the top fitting area of this tank car and onto its side shell. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected SHPX 207627. Inspection revealed the leak source at the liquid eduction line's closure cap. This closure cap was not tool tight. Responder tool tightened (3/4 turn) this closure cap using a pipe wrench by 2000 hrs. MDT, 3/31/10. SHPX 207627 was carefully setout of the train and moved to a containment area for spilled product neutralization and tank shell cleaning. Product spillage on SHPX 207627 was neutralized with baking soda/water solution by 0030 hrs. MDT, 4/01/2010. Ground spillage was neutralized with applications of soda ash and lime; and impacted soil was later excavated for appropriate disposal. No further product release was evident during subsequent rail movements of SHPX 207627 in the railyard.  One BNSF employee that discovered SHPX 207627 leaking, complained of product inhalation exposure. This employee was taken to a local hospital, examined and provided oxygen; and later released to return to work with no lost work days recorded.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On Thursday March 18th Andrew Leaman (FSTI driver) was in route to make a routine delivery of Sulfuric acid drums to a customer.  Andrew stopped at the parking lot of a Myers Elgin Sausage restaurant to check his load, when he noticed there was Sulfuric Acid leaking though the bottom of his trailer onto the asphalt.  He discovered that one of the drums had been punctured by a raised nail head imbedded in a pallet that it was secured to.  The puncture was at the very bottom of the drum close to the edge.  The puncture size was about as big as standard eraser head on the end of a pencil.  Andrew was able to turn the drum over onto its side to stop the drum from leaking any further. He then took the appropriate measures to contain the spill with pads, socks and absorbent material.  Approximately 5 gallons of material had leaked from the drum onto the asphalt parking lot.  Estimated duration of release - 15 minutes.  He immediately called the office and reported the incident to Brady Hamilton after he was able to contain the spill.  Our emergency response contractor, Environmental Mgt, was then called to initiate a cleanup and dispose of the neutralized material.  The time was approximately 4:00 pm.  In the meantime Brady Hamilton and Chris Thompson rushed to the scene to help secure the area.  Brady and Chris arrived at approximately 5:00pm. TAS Environmental (cleanup contractor of Enviromental Mgt) arrived on the scene at approximately 6pm.  The punctured drum was put into a overpack and everything else was neutralized, wiped down and disposed of by the company.  They completed their work at approximately 8:00 pm that night.
column169: Corrective Action-We have gone to pallet-less drum deliveries to avoid these types of problems in the future.

column168: Driver began to unload by opening the internal valve and then the external valve. He noticed that there was no product flowing. He than closed the external valve and returned to the tractor to charge the air tanks with air that supplies air to the internal valve. When he pushed the trailer air button in it automatically shut off the air flow charging the tanker. This allowed product to back feed through the air system and leak from underneath the tractor.The operator at the facility immediately constructed a small berm of soil which contained the product.
column169: We notified all the drivers of the situation and how it happened. We advised all the drivers using this tanker that the air tanks need to be fully charged with air before trying to open the internal valve. The valve did not actually fail, it works a little harder because of age and will only open when air tanks are fully charged.

column168: 1. Customer mixed incompatible wastes (paint related base coating with activator) in the same drum.  2. Drum was shipped from shipper’s location by Univar on Friday, March 26, 2010 and stored in transit at the Univar site for delivery to the Veolia Treatment Storage and Disposal Facility (TSDF) on Monday March 29, 2010.  3. Prior to final shipment to the TSDF, the driver checked his load, noticed an odor and a skewed cubic yard box in the nose of the trailer.  4. ER contractor was called – truck was unloaded – drum/shipment identified.  5. Drum had ruptured under pressure – material was listed as a paint related liquid and was observed to be a polymerized solid without any free liquid that caused a failure on the bottom seam of the drum.  6. Polymerized paint related material appeared to have rapidly left the drum without any release outside of the transport vehicle.  7. Truck and drums were cleaned.  8. Polymerized solids and cleaning liquids were containerized for proper disposal.
column169: We are recommending:  1. A review of the incident with the generator of the waste, our Customer Service personnel, and our drivers with the suggestion of refresher training on compatibility, profiling, communication, and the consequences of mixing incompatible materials.    2. In the Customer Service/profiling phase of future shipment we suggest an emphasized review of profile information, constituents, and potential incompatibilities with the customer.

column169: DO NOT STACK HEAVY FREIGHT ON 5-GALLON PAILS OF CHEMICALS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO ENSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAIINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY   FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ONE TOP!  USE PLENTLY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: The driver was using air pressure to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  Plant operator said there was plenty of room in their tank. column168: The driver was using air pressure to transfer product from the cargo tank to a single fill line that equalized from one storage tank to another.    He was using 90' of transfer hose and had the discharge valve open only 1/3 way.  The driver shut down periodically to let them equalize and check the level in the tanks.  The last time he checked it was 1 foot from the top.  Shortly thereafter, the air hit the tank and forced about 5 gallons out of the top of the first tank.  driver shut down immediately.  Spill went into a containment area around the tank and the customer hosed it to their waste system.
column169: The customer asked the driver what could be done differently to prevent future issues. Driver thought he had gone slow enough to let the tanks equalize.  He thought maybe another connector on the top of the tanks but wasn't sure if that would work.

column168: A driver arrived at approximately 15:30 and hooked to a trailer which contained the Combustible Liquid N.O.S. shipment. Once the trailer was opened it became apparent that a tote containing the petroleum hydrocarbon was leaking from the bottom valve. The tote was placed on a skid and three sheets of cardboard. Inside the trailer, the spilled product was covered with absorbent and swept into a salvage drum. Spilled product that was found on the ground was also covered with absorbent and swept into asalvage drum for disposal. After analyzing the tote, it was determined the valve had been loosened after contact with a forklift. Once the valve was tightened the dripping stopped. The shipment was sent on the the final destination.

column168: ON 03/16/2010 AT 1016 HRS CSDT I WAS ADVISED BY TRAINMASTER M. CAROLL, THAT AN ODOR WAS EMANATING FROM CAR CELX 23001 RESIDUAL/LAST CONTAINED ETHYL ACETATE WHILE CAR WAS IN THE RIP REPAIR FACILITY FOR AN FRA DEFECT UNRELATED TO THE TANK.  RIP REPAIR FACILITY PERSONNEL SHOVED CAR OUT OF THE BUILDING AND PROCEEDED TO VENT BUILDING.  WHILE IN ROUTE TO SCENE I CONTACTED HAZMAT CONTRACTOR, "MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL" AND REQUESTED THAT THEY RESPOND TO SCENE ALSO.  UPON ARRIVAL TO SCENE I CONDUCTED A GROUND EXAMINATION OF THE RAILCAR AND NOTED NO VISIBLE LEAKS OR VAPORS.  I SUBSEQUENTLY CLIMBED ON TOP OF CAR AND DETECTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON THE A-END OF THE CAR AND ALSO NOTED ODOR COMING FROM UNDER THE MANWAY COVER.  I ALONG WITH DAVE ESTEP OF "MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL" CONDUCTED A BUBBLE TEST ON THE PRD AND THE MANWAY AND NOTED VAPOR ESCAPING AT A VERY MINOR RATE.  THE PRD WAS EXAMINED AND OUR FINDINGS NOTED THAT O-RINGS WERE NOT SEATED FOR REASONS UNKNOWN AND WE PROCEEDED TO RE-SEAT THE RINGS WHICH STOPPED THE VAPOR WHICH WAS CONFIRMED WITH TWO (2) BUBBLE TESTS.  WE THAN TURNED OUR ATTENTION TO THE MANWAY COVER AND NOTED THAT FIVE (5) OUT OF THE EIGHT (8) BOLTS SECURINMG THE MANWAY COVER WERE LOOSE AND IN PARTICULAR THE TWO (2) ON EACH SIDE OF THE HINGE.  WE SUBSEQUENTLY TIGHTENED ALL BOLTS AND CONDUCTED TWO (2) BUBBLE TESTS AND NOTED NO LEAKS.  THERE WAS NO EVACUATIONS OR INJURIES AND DURING THE REPAIR A SECURE PERIMETER WAS MAINTAINED BY RAILROAD PERSONNEL.
