column168: The driver was south bound on State Route 8 coming from Titusville heading toward Rouseville in Pennsylvania.  The tractor trailer rolled over and hit a bridge while negotiating a curve on Route 8 approximately 3 miles north of Rouseville.  The impact of the trailer with the bridge caused the tanker to be broken in two pieces.  One half of the trailer was still attached to the tractor which ended up on it's side on the bridge.  The other half ended up in the creek below the bridge.  The result of the crash caused the load of 7442 gallons of ultra low sulfur diesel to be released and catch on fire.  Some of the product that was release spilled into a stream below the bridge that flows into Oil Creek and the Allegheny River.  The fire and release continued for at least 2 hours before it was under control by emergency responders.    Upon notification of the accident we contacted McCutcheon Enterprises to dispatch an emergency responce cleanup team to the scene.  They along with the DEP , EPA and Fire Department contaned the fire and remaining hazardous material to the best of there ability.    In addition to the equipment damage and product loss there was about 300 feet of guard rail damaged as well as damage to the bridge that was struck by the equipment.  The damaged equipment was taken by Minich’s Towing and Klapec Trucking to Minich’s salvage yard located at 1682 Riverside Drive in Oil City, PA.  For information on the equipment contact Chris Minich at 814-676-2156.
column169: After the accident, in an effort to improve safe driving, we implemented training reviews and safety awareness programs for all active drivers.  We also altered starting times of drivers in an effort to allow drivers to be more rested before they begin there day.  This also allowed them to have more daylight conditions while driving.

column168: Rt. 31 Somers, Wi.: 3 N/B lanes. 3 S/B lanes. Truck and trailer were headed southbound on Rt. 31 in the middle lane at 50-55 mph. Speed limit is 55 mph. Road made a slight jog to the left and shoulder ends. The unit drifted to the right lane and then the right steer and drive tires went off the road and stayed parallel with the pavement for 48 feet.The driver over corrected turning the wheel to the left to avoid a mail box causing the tractor and trailer to rollover onto it's right side. The truck and trailer slid 197 feet coming to rest with the tractor in the center median and the trailer lying across the two left south bound lanes. The weight of the loaded tanker sliding the distance that it did,ground the right side of the tank down near the bulkheads at all four compartments causing several holes ranging in lengths of six to eighteen inches. All four compartments drained out in a very short time flowing south into a drainage sewer and west into a field. An off duty Kenosha County Serriffs Deputy was first on the scene and contacted emergency services. County workers and the Somers Fire Dept. contained the spill with sand and booms. A private environmental contractor was notified by A D Conner and took over containment and clean up. The driver was transported to the hospital where he was checked out and received a post accident drug and alcohol test. He was then questioned by Kenosha County Sheriffs Police and A D Conner safety officials and released. The tractor and trailer were up righted and towed to the company's storage yard where it was inspected by the Wisconsin DOT and then transported back to A D Conner in Frankfort II.
column169: Retrain drivers on the importance of keeping focused on the job at hand. Knowing that a mail box is a lot cheaper to replace than a tractor and trailer, not to mention the environmental clean up.

column168: PVS Transportation driver Kenneth Barton arrived at the Houston facility on Monday, March 29 at approximately 5:30 AM to start his work for the day.  Shortly after his arrival he attempted to depart the facility with tractor 187 and trailer 119.  Trailer 119 was loaded with Hydrochloric Acid loaded at PPG.  This load was to deliver on BOL 326168-1 to Albemarle in Pasadena, Texas at 6AM.      There has been ongoing constructions on the road in front of the Houston Facility.  Harris County had poured cement on the eastbound side of Haden Road that weekend and the cones were still up at the time of the incident.  All eastbound traffic was to use the temporary road on the south side of Haden Road. The driver was attempting to making a right turn onto the westbound side of Haden Road.  Due to the construction over the weekend, the lane was extremely narrow.  The driver attempted the turn 5 times before backing up on the scale to increase the turning space.  He attempted the turn 2 more times.  On the 7th try, the driver stopped, looked around and thought that he could complete the turn. As he was exiting, his back axles came off the pavement onto the soft 18 inch shoulder.  The ground gave way and the truck and trailer rolled into the ditch. The equipment, both truck and trailer, came to rest on the passenger side in the ditch. The crash box on the trailer was damaged and there was a slow leak coming from the air valve. The CPVC air valve had snapped off the trailer at the flange. The product was fuming. The driver sustained a small bump on his head but was otherwise uninjured.      The driver call dispatch and 911.  Mike Sellers arrived at the facility around 5:45 AM. The fire department was already on scene and the area had been shut down. Both the road and the railroad were shut down until 10:45 AM.  At 10:45 AM one lane of the road was reopened. The road was closed periodically until 10:30 PM on 3/29/10.  Andy Yaksic arrived on scene around 10:45 AM.  Oil Mop was called in to begin the remediation.      At 2:30 PM they started pumping the contents of trailer 119 into trailer 403A with a diaphragm pump, about 3627 gallons. The truck and trailer 119 was up righted around 9:00 PM. About 7 inches or 378 gallons of product was still on 119.     This leaves about 610 gallons of Hydrochloric Acid in the ditch. Sodium Bicarbonate was added to the ditch water in an effort to neutralize the material.  46,780 pounds of water was pumped from the ditch to trailer 117.  The material on 117 has a pH of 1.5. The liquid waste will be shipped out as hazardous waste by PSC.     Sodium Bicarbonate was added to the ground in an effort to neutralize the soil.  Six (6) 20 ton roll off boxes of soil have been filled with pH samples between 5 and 11.  This material will be shipped out as non hazardous waste to PSC.
column169: Root Cause(s) of Incident:  Driver failed to maintain control of his equipment while egressing from the Houston facility.     Contributing Factor(s):  Driver failed to stop trying to exit the facility until someone could assist him.  Weekend construction of Haden Road narrowed Westbound lane.  Poor design of Haden Road – Other facilities on Haden Road have expressed concerns about the design of this road especially while under construction.  PVS was already looking into adding additional concrete to increase the turning radius for trucks entering and exiting the facility.   Construction schedule was not properly communicated to PVS Technologies.  Harris County indicated that the road would be available for use on Monday morning.  There were no signs indicating that a left turn should have been made or a right turn should not have been made.  No signs indicating “DETOUR” or alternate routing.   Spill box was crushed resulting in damage to the air valve  The piping on the truck was polypropylene, had it been Teflon lined carbon steel the leak may  not have occurred.     Corrective Action(s):  The driver was given a citation for failure to maintain lane but was not issued any DOT citations.  Plant Manager to make it mandatory for all trucks leaving the Facility to exit via the scale lane.  County to add 15 feet of concrete to cover the culvert.

column168: On the morning of March 1, 2010, my driver, Mr. Joshua Folse, was delivering a load of methanol, approximately 7400 — 7500 gallons, from IMTT in St. Rose, LA to C-Port # 2 in Fourchon, LA. Mr. Folse stopped at the Cajun Truck Plaza which is located at the corner of AC. Rappelet Road and N.J. Theriot Road in Port Fourchon, LA. Mr. Folse stopped to use the restroom and get a drink before proceeding to his unloading destination, since there was already another truck currently offloading in front of him.   At approximately 10:30 AM, he proceeded to leave the Cajun Truck Plaza through the rear exit, which exits on 1st Street, which is also the road that is the entrance for C-Port # 2. There is a large hole in the pavement directly in front of the exit, which Mr. Folse had to pass through on his way out of the facility. Mr. Folse made the normal large left hand turn, while still in 1st gear to insure that he was able to make the turn under control. He was watching in his mirrors to insure that he was able to make the turn as safe as possible. While making the turn onto the road, 1st Street, all of the eight (8) tires of the rear axles were still on the ground, but the rear driver’s outside tire was approximately four to six inches over the edge, but the majority of the tire was still on the pavement. The edge of the driveway was rounded a one point, with an approximate two and 1/2 foot drop to the bottom of the ditch. When Mr. Folse’s wet tires hit this rounded section of the driveway and with the weight of the trailer, this was too much for the traction of the tires to overcome and the trailer slipped into the ditch. The rear axle of the trailer went into the ditch, which caused the trailer to come to rest on the driver side of the tank trailer. The rear axle of the truck, while remaining connected to the trailer, twisted in the air to the driver’s side of the vehicle. The front tires of the truck remained in contact with the pavement of the road entire time of the incident.
column169: AFTER THE ACCIDENT ON MARCH 1, 2010, ALL OF OUR DRIVERS WERE RE-TRAINED ON THE PROPER ACCIDENT PROTOCOLS SET UP FORTH BY OUR COMPANY.  THE LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH ALL DRIVERS AND THE IMPORTANCE OF VERIFYING THAT THE DOME LID AND WASHOUT CAPS WAS HEAVILY STRESSED.  AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT, WE HAVE ALSO BEGAN TO REVIEW AND REVISE OUR SPCC AND ACCIDENT PROCEDURES TO MAKE SURE THAT THEY ARE UP TO DATE AND CURRENTLY IDENTIFY THE PROPER INFORMATION NEEDED IN CASE OF AN ACCIDENT.

column168: Approximately 250 gallons of unleaded gasoline was released during the delivery of fuel to the premium underground storage tank (UST) on March 17, 2010. The release filled the spill containment bucket and flowed over the concrete tank pad until it reached the surrounding asphalt. The gasoline then flowed in a southeasterly direction and entered a stormwater catch basin located approximately 45 feet from the tank pad. The gasoline accumulated in this catch basin and then entered the outfall structure and traveled through the subgrade piping to a second catch basin. This process continued as the gasoline eventually accumulated in four consecutive on-site catch basins located to the north of the Turkey Hill store building. The fifth catch basin in the on-)t stprm se_w.er retork did riot contain an.y   indicating that the gasoline released at the site was contained on the Turkey Hill property and did not adversely affect any surface waters downgradient of the site.   Upon discovery of the release, the Hazle Township Fire Department was called to the site by Turkey Hill store employees. The fire department’s cleanup activities consisted primarily of applying granular adsorbent material to the ground surface. The fuel delivery company, Falcon Oil Company of Blakely, Pennsylvania, also retained SCE Environmental Group of Dickson City, Pennsylvania, to perform a cleanup of the spilled product. SCE’s activities, which were discussed with the DEP representatives present at the site, included flushing the on-site storm sewer system and recovering of the water and product mixture.   Strong petroleum odors were observed in the store building soon after the release occurred, indicating that some of the released product infiltrated into the subsurface, presumably through joints and cracks in the concrete and asphalt paving. Due to the elevated vapors, the building was evacuated. Measured volatile organic vapor concentrations in the building, as recorded by Liberty with a calibrated photoionization detector (PID), were as high as 60 parts per million (ppm). Screening of the tankfield observation wells for organic vapors yielded PID deflections of 2,518 ppm from OW-i and 2,145 ppm from OW-2.   Upon observing gasoline vapors in the store building, Turkey Hill retained Liberty to install a sub-slab vapor extraction (VE) system at the site to mitigate the intrusion of gasoline vapors into the building. The VE system included PVC piping running from beneath the building’s floor slab to the ground surface, a 1.5 horsepower blower, a moisture knockout vessel, and twin 55-gallon vapor—phase activated carbon drums in series. Upon startup of the VE system on the evening of March 17, 2010, vapors in the building diminished significantly and the store was able to reopen. column168: On March 12, 2010 in Bellaire, Tx, one of our transport trucks was carrying a load of unleaded gasoline for the City of Houston to 3202 S. Dairy Ashford. The equipment was late model and in good operating condition. The weather was clear and the traffic was light. As the driver made a proper left turn at about 4mph the vehicle overturned. As soon as the company was notified of the accident we immediately called the National Response Center, the Bellaire Police Department, and Garner Environmental (our first responder). The release lasted approximately 3 hours releasing 2,400 gallons of unleaded gasoline. The spill was immediately cleaned up and resolved. Both the Houston Hazmat and the City of Bellaire Police Department found no apparent reason for the accident. The driver nor the carrier were cited for the incident.
column169: The accident investigation by the Bellaire Police Department and one conducted internally by the carrier yielded no conclusion to the cause of the accident. Oil Patch Brazos Valley has never had a comparable incident in 22 years of operations. We continue to practice our standard safety policies to prevent any and all accidents.

column168: Passengers boarded F9 flight 235 (BNA/DEN) in Nashville and were at Gate A38 in DEN to board F9 flight 789 (DEN/LAS).  At the gate, they were observed with a Portable Oxygen Concentrator (POC). When asked by the Frontier agent if it was a POC or if it was actual oxygen, they stated that it was a POC but then volunteered that she also had a bottle of oxygen in a black closed canvas bag she was carrying. The bottle was full, with the regulator on and valve closed.     The passengers were informed of the regulations regarding compressed gases. The passenger emptied the bottle but was unable to remove the valve/regulator to visually inspect the bottle as empty.  The passenger decided to leave the empty bottle in Denver and make arrangements to have it picked up and mailed to her home in Nashville on her way back through Denver on Saturday, March 6th.     The passengers stated that both gate agents and flight crew at BNA had said nothing about the bottle.  The DEN Frontier staff tried to assist the passenger in removing the top. They called maintenance to see if they had a wrench that would take it off, which they didn’t.     The agents provided the passengers with a printout of Frontier’s medical use oxygen policy from the website (www.frontierairlines.com).  They stated that the information was not what they saw earlier at the website.
column169: 1. This apparent violation involves a passenger (Janice Owens) who failed to notify Frontier Airlines that she was carrying medical use oxygen in addition to a Portable Oxygen Concentrator (POC).  The medical use oxygen policy for Frontier Airlines is as follows:     medical oxygen onboard  Cylinders of compressed or liquefied medical oxygen can't be accepted onboard or in checked baggage for any of our flights.      (http://www.frontierairlines.com/frontier/plan-book/travel-info-services/special-needs)    3.  As part of a Comprehensive fix, Frontier Airlines will provide notices and additional awareness training at call centers and passenger handling locations on the need to probe further into situations where a Portable Oxygen Concentrator is declared for carriage and use onboard by a passenger.    4. Primary responsibility for the monitoring and oversight of the proposed manual and training changes to create further awareness of hidden hazmats resides with the Director of Flight Operations safety and the Director of Operations for Frontier Airlines.

column168: The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

The pail was unloaded with leakage noted.  Examination of the pail revealed the pail had a loose cap/lid and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap/lid was secured. Undamaged product was returned to the shipper.  The damaged product was properly disposed of in accordance with Federal Regulations.
